rating_comment:
The delivery confidence assessment awarded at the Infrastructure Projects Authority (and associated Major Projects Review Group) Review in October 2015 reflected the significant progress the Programme has made since the previous rating given in March 2014. 
In awarding an Amber delivery confidence assessment, the IPA acknowledged that the Universal Credit Programme:
Â has made considerable progress;
Â has strong leadership in place;
Â is integrated with partners with stakeholders actively engaged (with plans in place to strengthen further);
Â has a single agreed end-to-end delivery plan; 
Â is rolling out at pace Universal Credit nationally to single unemployed claimants across GB, and 
Â is demonstrating evidence of positive Labour Market effects.        
The Programme has implemented all recommendations from earlier IPA reviews. The latest IPA recommendations have been accepted by the Programme, and action owners have been assigned and implementation action plans drawn up. All recommendations and action plans will be subject to regular monitoring and independent scrutiny to ensure all necessary action is being taken to address and close the recommendations at the earliest opportunity.

description_aims:
The Fraud, Error and Debt programme forms a key part of the GovernmentÂs commitment to reduce fraud and error in the welfare system. The programme aims to improve the DepartmentÂs ability to prevent, detect and respond to fraud and error, and to leverage the benefits from increased sharing of intelligence within DWP and across Government organisations.

The key objectives are: 

Â to optimise the use of HMRCÂs earnings, employment and pensions data Â for Universal Credit and other income-related benefits, including working with local authorities on Housing Benefit;  

Â to have a debt and deduction recovery solution in place enabling existing cases of DWP, HMRC, local authority debt and other additional third party deductions to be recovered on migration to Universal Credit (UC); 

Â to deliver the Single Fraud Investigation Service (SFIS) project to provide cross-government anti-fraud services; 

Â to provide members of the public with a userÂfriendly and confidential service to report benefit fraud online; 

Â to increase emphasis on prevention and improved support for detection and investigative action by delivering a business rules-based routing and management system; and 

Â to deliver an online collection service, supporting additional debt recoveries.

To manage the safe exit of HMRC's ASPIRE IT contract that expires in June 2017. The Programme Aims and Objectives are: The Programme aim for the scope reflected in the Business Case is to:
Â achieve a safe transition from the ASPIRE contract to the new HMRC IT operating and sourcing model, enabling HMRCÂs digital and data transformation and deliver the benefits of the new model thereafter.

The Programme objectives for the scope reflected in the Business Case are to:
Â Ensure there is continuity of IT supply to the Department and its customers once the current contractual arrangements through the ASPIRE contracts expire in June 2017;
Â Ensure that new sourcing arrangements provide better value for money, drive out savings compared to current baseline and are market aligned and consistent with Government standards for ICT contracts and IT delivery;Â Ensure the operating model for IT in HMRC is transformed to enable HMRCÂs digital and data transformation and to ensure that changes can be made more flexibly and at greater speed through a new target operating model, sourcing model and re-engineered processes;
Â Ensure HMRC has the capacity and capability to operate its new IT operating model on a sustainable basis;
Â Ensure the transition from ASPIRE contracts to the new operating model is as smooth as possible with minimal disruption to service (same or better SLAs) and project delivery (time, cost, quality as agreed for each project) during the transition period.

